description.narrative: (Malawi): ONSE activity supports the reduction of maternal, newborn, and child mortality. Focus areas include maternal, neonatal, and child health; malaria; water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH); nutrition; TB; and family planning (FP) services. Activities support objectives under Preventing Child and Maternal Deaths, FP 2020, and the President's Malaria Initiative. ONSE will scale up effective, equitable, locally adapted, and evidence-based interventions to reach poor, marginalized, and vulnerable people in 16 target districts. It will advance quality of care efforts through performance-based financing, community scorecards, and implementation of Ministry of Health and Population's roadmap on reducing neonatal and maternal morbidity and mortality. It will continue research on innovative service delivery models for integrated interventions such as group antenatal care and community-based intermittent presumptive treatment of malaria in pregnancy. ONSE supports sustainable access to WASH services. To address low TB case-finding rates among children, it conducts TB contact tracing in high burden areas, prioritizing children living with adult pulmonary TB patients. It will also build the capacity of health workers to conduct contact investigations. ONSE will strengthen supervision and management for facilities through the utilization of a tool to document and resolve challenges in health facilities. It supports health governance by establishing active links between civil society and quality improvement activities. ONSE strengthens capacity of district officials in governance, management of human resources for health, and the use of data for decision-making. It engages in community mobilization to improve healthy practices and promotes health-seeking behaviors. The activity will facilitate community dialogue and civic participation to promote the empowerment of women and youth as well as male involvement, a U.S. Foreign Policy priority....... ..... .
